</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=frodlin7th>Frodlin7th</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>/cons RED</span><br>  Posts: 375<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/28/03 3:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3073.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Taunt - Mezzed Mobs - Seems to not fit the current theor</span><hr size=1> The prevailing &quot;theories&quot; aeem to be true regardless of the doubts of others.<br>
<br>
1. A successful taunt will place you at the top of the hate list by *some* amount (no one's sure what that amount is).  <br>
<br>
2. A failed taunt will do absolutely nothing.<br>
<br>
There are two ways to verify this.<br>
<br>
1. Taunt a mob which is not KOS which has a &quot;successful taunt&quot; emote.   Such as city guards at a location where you're not KOS.<br>
<br>
If you get no message, I absolutely positively guarantee you without a shadow of a doubt, that you'll not be attacked.    This has been done by myself and many others.  No attack = no hate.  What this means is that a failed taunt does absolutely nothing period with regards to hatelist manipulation.<br>
<br>
If you DO get a message, then you WILL be attacked... period.   This means that taunt *does* generate some amount of hate, be it one or more, no one is sure.  Any conjecture on amounts is merely that, guesses... shots in the dark, and totally unreliable to base any claims on.<br>
<br>
2. If a mob is aggroed upon by someone else, or multiple people, will a successful taunt place you automatically to the top of the aggro list?<br>
<br>
The only way to find this out, is to taunt intelligent mobs, those with a message which verifies a successful taunt.  (I'll teach you to interfere with me target).    Mezzed mobs are perfect because they retain their hate lists, and their hate lists seem to adjust even while mezzed (i.e. you can't taunt one, then go fight for 5 mins and come back expecting to be on top still, any aggro generating activity will be applied to the person who engaged in it).  In hate, the way to tell is Clerics of Innorruuk.   Taunt them... no emote = failed taunt.. emote = successful taunt.  If NO ONE else is doing something around you, /assist the mob and see if he's aggro on you.  My money is he will be.   If you taunt, then get a CH, then you've potentially altered the hatelist from the point where you taunted, and can't blame the mechanics of taunt for this, just your own timing of taunt.<br>
<br>
